301
00:17:37,640 --> 00:17:38,560
Yes, that was our meet cute.

302
00:17:38,600 --> 00:17:39,120
That was our meet.

303
00:17:40,200 --> 00:17:41,200
Hollywood parlance.

304
00:17:41,200 --> 00:17:41,920
But he did meet.

305
00:17:43,020 --> 00:17:45,000
So here's the story.

306
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:45,260
Yeah.

307
00:17:45,780 --> 00:17:51,160
I grew up next to a guy that I revered when I grew up in the Bay Area.

308
00:17:51,740 --> 00:17:54,420
In a place called Walnut Creek, which is East Bay.

309
00:17:55,220 --> 00:18:05,260
And we lived right next door to this family where there was a guy named John Harrington, his wife Lois, his two daughters.

310
00:18:05,480 --> 00:18:06,200
I'm not going to name them.

311
00:18:07,500 --> 00:18:11,120
His daughters were in between my brother and I.

312
00:18:11,220 --> 00:18:12,940
So I was the oldest of the four kids.

313
00:18:13,060 --> 00:18:13,980
My brother was the youngest.

314
00:18:14,500 --> 00:18:18,400
And I mean, we literally lived right next door and there was like one gate between us.

315
00:18:18,640 --> 00:18:20,980
And we lived on these pretty big pieces of property.

316
00:18:20,980 --> 00:18:22,640
So we didn't have any other real neighbors.

317
00:18:22,760 --> 00:18:24,380
It was just us, kids growing up.

318
00:18:24,940 --> 00:18:27,420
And John was a man's man.

319
00:18:27,620 --> 00:18:30,320
He was all the things I wanted to be.

320
00:18:30,360 --> 00:18:31,220
My dad was an artist.

321
00:18:31,620 --> 00:18:33,040
And so I wanted to be an athlete.

322
00:18:33,140 --> 00:18:33,820
I wanted to do all these things.

323
00:18:33,960 --> 00:18:39,680
John taught me how to throw a football, got me into football, taught me how to hold a gun, you know, shoot a BB gun.

324
00:18:39,780 --> 00:18:40,680
Just all these things.

325
00:18:40,840 --> 00:18:43,620
And loved my dad, but he was an artist.

326
00:18:43,760 --> 00:18:45,280
He wasn't interested in any of this stuff.

327
00:18:45,280 --> 00:18:48,860
So I became, he was the, he was like a surrogate father to me.

328
00:18:49,860 --> 00:18:52,820
Cut to, we move away six years later.

329
00:18:53,020 --> 00:18:54,320
We stay in touch, the families.

330
00:18:55,160 --> 00:18:57,120
And then I get a phone call.

331
00:18:57,300 --> 00:18:58,580
I've just graduated from high school.

332
00:18:58,680 --> 00:18:59,320
It's 1981.

333
00:19:00,020 --> 00:19:01,160
And I'm going to UCLA.

334
00:19:01,580 --> 00:19:07,620
And I had, John had suggested that I go to Stanford, which was his alma mater, but I'm going to UCLA to be a theater major.

335
00:19:07,620 --> 00:19:11,540
So he calls me up and he says, you know, what are you doing?

336
00:19:11,600 --> 00:19:13,120
And I can't believe you didn't go to Stanford.

337
00:19:13,320 --> 00:19:15,720
He goes, listen, I got a new job.

338
00:19:15,900 --> 00:19:17,160
I'm back East now.

339
00:19:18,220 --> 00:19:23,800
And I'd, I'd like you and maybe a couple of friends to drive our cars across the country.

340
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:30,120
Oh, and our dog, bringing our dog with you and some other stuff that we left in the garage, but I'll pay you guys.

341
00:19:30,120 --> 00:19:34,360
And then when you get back here, I'll show you around DC and then I'll fly you back.

342
00:19:34,620 --> 00:19:36,500
I'm thinking, what a great summer.

343
00:19:36,500 --> 00:19:37,980
Sweet deal for a college kid.

344
00:19:37,980 --> 00:19:38,180
Right.

345
00:19:38,280 --> 00:19:41,160
It's like, uh, it was the in between high school and college.

346
00:19:41,160 --> 00:19:42,800
So I'm thinking, sure, I'll, I can do that.

347
00:19:43,280 --> 00:19:58,980
So he didn't say anything about what his job was, but actually we knew something was going on because about a year earlier or so we had been approached the family by some like NSA or like CIA or someone that come in and asked a bunch of questions.

348
00:19:58,980 --> 00:20:05,140
I guess they were doing like a background character check on him, but they didn't tell us what the job was, but we knew it was something with the government.

349
00:20:05,140 --> 00:20:08,100
And he has just moved back to Langley Farms, Virginia.

350
00:20:10,100 --> 00:20:20,360
So by the way, in, in 1981, we now know John Harrington was the undersecretary of the Navy for, I believe, development and, or procurement or something like that.

351
00:20:20,360 --> 00:20:24,260
And I, I believe he went through Stanford on a Naval ROTC scholarship.

352
00:20:24,640 --> 00:20:25,040
Okay.

353
00:20:25,180 --> 00:20:25,960
So Navy.

354
00:20:26,840 --> 00:20:30,660
And he will later become the secretary of energy in the second term.

355
00:20:31,340 --> 00:20:32,140
Department of Energy.

356
00:20:32,340 --> 00:20:32,760
There you go.

357
00:20:32,760 --> 00:20:35,680
So none of this means anything to me.

358
00:20:35,740 --> 00:20:36,700
He's just a great friend.

359
00:20:36,800 --> 00:20:38,020
He's like my surrogate dad.

360
00:20:38,560 --> 00:20:39,700
The drive across the country.

361
00:20:39,860 --> 00:20:42,980
I don't know why we weren't killed or put in jail many times.

362
00:20:43,640 --> 00:20:45,460
That's a whole other movie I've never written.

363
00:20:46,140 --> 00:20:47,440
We get to his house.

364
00:20:48,200 --> 00:20:53,300
That night when he comes home where everyone's waiting to have dinner, because it's going to be like this reunion.

365
00:20:53,300 --> 00:21:04,680
And, um, I remember kind of like waiting at the window, kind of waiting to see when I was in a black Lincoln town car pulls up and he gets out of the backseat and there's two secret service people that come in.

366
00:21:04,760 --> 00:21:07,420
And I noticed he has a briefcase handcuffed to his wrist.

367
00:21:08,100 --> 00:21:15,020
They walk him into the house and into kind of the, off the entryway into his office and they go back and I'm kind of watching from a distance.

368
00:21:15,100 --> 00:21:16,420
No one will even make eye contact with me.

369
00:21:16,440 --> 00:21:20,700
And I'm watching from a distance and he puts it into a wall safe, right?

370
00:21:20,700 --> 00:21:24,280
One of the secret service people leaves and the other one stays in the house.

371
00:21:25,660 --> 00:21:27,840
I'm thinking, who is this guy?

372
00:21:28,120 --> 00:21:30,680
Like, but he comes, hey, Brian, how's it going?

373
00:21:30,840 --> 00:21:32,960
We have a big dinner and everything's great.

374
00:21:33,040 --> 00:21:37,520
And then afterwards he's like, hey, why don't you and I go out onto the veranda and catch up?

375
00:21:38,440 --> 00:21:44,820
So when we were growing up, he was not just like pad-ass, but he was Calvinist.

376
00:21:44,860 --> 00:21:48,020
So he was very strict about certain things.

377
00:21:48,020 --> 00:21:54,100
We go into the back patio and he brings a big bottle of Jim Beam and he's pouring himself two fingers as we're talking.

378
00:21:54,520 --> 00:21:56,060
He looks haggard.

379
00:21:56,180 --> 00:22:00,520
He looks, you know, old, like very much older, but also just heavy now.

380
00:22:01,420 --> 00:22:02,480
He's a different guy.

381
00:22:04,320 --> 00:22:06,080
I'm sitting there talking with him.

382
00:22:06,160 --> 00:22:06,780
We're catching up.

383
00:22:06,820 --> 00:22:09,020
He's giving me shit about not going to Stanford.

384
00:22:09,480 --> 00:22:11,700
And I'm like, okay, all of that's great.

385
00:22:12,140 --> 00:22:13,400
What is your job?

386
00:22:13,740 --> 00:22:15,560
And he goes, I can't really talk about it.

387
00:22:15,560 --> 00:22:20,260
I, you know, it's, I'm working for the government now he was Reagan's advance man in his campaign.

388
00:22:20,380 --> 00:22:22,820
He was one of the reasons that he helped Reagan get elected.

389
00:22:23,140 --> 00:22:31,080
There's a whole history between John's wife, Lois Haight, who's, I think one of her family members was a governor of California back in the day.

390
00:22:31,080 --> 00:22:35,060
And so politics, Republican, you know, they went way back.

391
00:22:35,060 --> 00:22:38,860
At any rate, he's working for Reagan because Reagan trusts him.

392
00:22:39,640 --> 00:22:41,760
And this is a super smart guy.

393
00:22:42,260 --> 00:22:46,400
And now he's telling me, I can't tell you what the job is.

394
00:22:47,260 --> 00:22:48,120
It's classified.

395
00:22:48,580 --> 00:22:51,400
And I said, okay, well, I don't, what does that even mean?

396
00:22:51,420 --> 00:22:54,740
And he goes, look, I have a higher clearance level than the president.

397
00:22:54,740 --> 00:22:59,320
Now, 1981, oops, 18 years old.

398
00:22:59,420 --> 00:23:01,280
I was not a standout in civics.

399
00:23:01,420 --> 00:23:03,380
I was like, that's impossible.

400
00:23:03,480 --> 00:23:06,100
The president, there is nothing higher than the president.

401
00:23:06,840 --> 00:23:12,640
How, how, how could the guy who lived next door to me have higher classification than the president?

402
00:23:12,640 --> 00:23:15,280
But this is not a guy who lies.

403
00:23:15,760 --> 00:23:18,880
Like, so I'm looking at this guy and I'm thinking, what?

404
00:23:19,320 --> 00:23:20,840
I'm like, okay.

405
00:23:21,700 --> 00:23:24,900
And I said, well, how did, so how did you get that job?

406
00:23:24,980 --> 00:23:31,040
And he said, well, I, I was briefed for months in an underground facility in West Virginia.

407
00:23:33,020 --> 00:23:35,400
Again, this is the guy you grew up with.

408
00:23:35,400 --> 00:23:39,400
Like this, I'm like looking at this person, like, I don't, I don't even know who this man is anymore.

409
00:23:39,400 --> 00:23:43,840
And I said, what, what was that like?

410
00:23:43,880 --> 00:23:46,300
And he said, well, I used to cry myself to sleep every night.

411
00:23:47,440 --> 00:23:58,080
That's, by the way, when he said that to me at this lunch, I just got shiver, you know, because a tough guy is crying himself to sleep every night.

412
00:23:58,560 --> 00:24:00,540
What's it take for that to happen?

413
00:24:00,900 --> 00:24:01,080
Yeah.

414
00:24:01,120 --> 00:24:01,280
Yeah.

415
00:24:01,380 --> 00:24:06,720
And even if he's exaggerating, I couldn't have imagined him crying himself to sleep once.

416
00:24:06,900 --> 00:24:07,080
Right.

417
00:24:07,080 --> 00:24:11,420
So I said, well, I don't, what, what would make you cry yourself to sleep?

418
00:24:11,460 --> 00:24:16,020
And he goes, Brent, this is not the, the world I thought I was bringing my daughters into.

419
00:24:18,060 --> 00:24:20,900
I'm thinking, well, I'm like your son.

420
00:24:22,500 --> 00:24:25,020
What is this world that we're in?

421
00:24:25,460 --> 00:24:28,040
And so I pressed him on and he kept saying, I can't talk about that.

422
00:24:28,080 --> 00:24:28,900
I can't talk about it.

423
00:24:28,940 --> 00:24:30,700
I can, this is like classified information.

424
00:24:30,700 --> 00:24:41,480
And finally, after he'd had a couple of drinks, he said, all right, look, I know when you were growing up, you were into science fiction and comic books and all that stuff.

425
00:24:41,740 --> 00:24:42,620
I can tell you this.

426
00:24:43,220 --> 00:24:44,020
Aliens are real.

427
00:24:44,220 --> 00:24:44,920
They're here.

428
00:24:45,040 --> 00:24:45,880
And I've seen them.

429
00:24:45,880 --> 00:24:48,060
Just like that.

430
00:24:48,680 --> 00:24:50,360
Just like here, I'll throw you a bone kid.

431
00:24:51,480 --> 00:24:56,620
Now I honestly, at that point in my life, I hadn't thought a lot about aliens.

432
00:24:56,740 --> 00:24:57,920
I wasn't into aliens.

433
00:24:58,060 --> 00:25:02,680
This wasn't a thing in my life, but this felt huge.

434
00:25:02,680 --> 00:25:04,280
Like I couldn't wrap my brain around it.

435
00:25:04,280 --> 00:25:07,580
And I said, well, are they alive?

436
00:25:08,160 --> 00:25:12,140
And he paused and he said, I can't say.

437
00:25:12,940 --> 00:25:14,860
I said, you can't say or you won't say.

438
00:25:14,900 --> 00:25:16,160
And he said, I can't say.

439
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:20,500
And I kind of just left at that.

440
00:25:20,640 --> 00:25:24,120
And then I came back at him with, okay, well, hold on a second.

441
00:25:24,880 --> 00:25:29,440
If what you're saying is true, how does everyone not know about it?

442
00:25:29,560 --> 00:25:31,500
And he said, oh, lots of people know about it.

443
00:25:31,500 --> 00:25:37,160
81, you could walk into any bookstore and you're going to find all sorts of books on

444
00:25:37,160 --> 00:25:38,440
the shelves with lots of truth.

445
00:25:38,820 --> 00:25:43,140
But right next to them are the books that we publish full of propaganda.

446
00:25:43,520 --> 00:25:46,600
It's a multi-billion dollar campaign to cover up the truth.

447
00:25:47,840 --> 00:25:53,420
Now in 81, I, the other thing that struck me was I didn't, I don't know that I'd heard

448
00:25:53,420 --> 00:25:54,820
the term billion before.

449
00:25:55,220 --> 00:25:58,980
So I'm like, like everything is blowing my mind right now.

450
00:25:58,980 --> 00:26:05,340
And I'm thinking what, like I just had not considered any of this.

451
00:26:05,340 --> 00:26:10,120
And I was like, okay, why is the truth have to be covered up?

452
00:26:10,740 --> 00:26:12,940
Like you're telling me, okay, aliens are real.

453
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:13,960
Okay, great.

454
00:26:14,120 --> 00:26:14,560
What else?

455
00:26:14,900 --> 00:26:19,440
And he said, look, we live in a God fearing country.

456
00:26:19,440 --> 00:26:27,820
Again, 1981, there's only one thing that keeps this world spinning, gives everybody the control

457
00:26:27,820 --> 00:26:28,360
they need.

458
00:26:28,600 --> 00:26:30,020
That's the global economy.

459
00:26:30,400 --> 00:26:37,260
If you disrupt that by taking away the reason for people to live their lives, everything

460
00:26:37,260 --> 00:26:41,280
falls apart and governments of the world will not be able to control the populace.

461
00:26:41,280 --> 00:26:47,040
